<br>
One of the greatest deterrents for me, as a Wizard playing in EverQuest, to gaining experience was that I was constantly nagged by the fact that I could gain so much more experience while quadding, but this lonely solo experience was definitely something that I detested. Why play a MMORPG if you're not going to interact with people? The answer to that might very well be that the type of people who prefer solo'ing are likely the type of people who are eager to show off their accomplishments in an anti-social fashion, or, conversely, the type of people who just don't have time for the lengthy setup in groups (or who don't see the benefit of grouping).<br>
<br>
Increasing the experience inherent to grouping will address both major concerns above.<br>
<br>
With Shadowbane making experience-gathering silly (most characters basically finish leveling in a few weeks, rather than the months-to-years that EverQuest requires), and WoW poised to make progression less experience-based and more encounter/quest-based, EverQuest has to dramatically redefine its progression model if it hopes to remain competitive. As predicted, the competition is already prompting some positive changes over at SOE.<br>
<br>
The extend to which this improvement is successful remains to be seen, but I am optimistic that through the competition that SOE is facing, EverQuest will become more and more accessible to the casual player, and hardcore players - those that constitute the very active, but from a commercial standpoint, smaller userbase - will take a back-seat. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.kaelon.com/images/kaesiggy2.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
